0.body: Rant is an all-purpose templating and procedural text generation language. This document is a work-in-progress and is not normative. It only applies to the upcoming version 4 of the Rant language.
0.title: Introduction

10.body: Blocks serve several purposes in Rant, ranging from simple element selection to collections and even loops. They can contain any kind of Rant code—even other blocks.
10.title: Use cases

100.body: Defines the variable varname and sets it to value. If value is not specified, the variable is initialized to <>.
100.title: [def: varname; [value]]

101.body: Prints the value of the variable varname.
101.title: [get: varname]

102.body: Sets the variable varname to value.
102.title: [set: varname; value]

104.body: A block is a section of a Rant program subdivided into zero or more parts. Blocks act as variable scopes and can be combined with various constructs to produce a wide variety of behaviors.
104.title: Block

105.body: Block attributes provide a way to customize the resolver's behavior through the variable system, such as changing iteration count.
105.title: Block attributes

106.body: A channel is an independent stream of output from a Rant program. Programs may have more than one channel.
106.title: Channel

107.body: A construct is a group of one or more runtime variables can be used to interact with the Rant runtime and customize various aspects of program behavior.
107.title: Construct

108.body: A formatter is a runtime component that mutates output in some way.
108.title: Formatter

109.body: A fragment is a sequence of any non-whitespace, non-reserved characters found in a Rant program.
109.title: Fragment

11.body:
In their simplest form, blocks resolve a single element from their body and add it to the output. # Randomly prints "Heads" or "Tails" with uniform probability
{Heads|Tails} By default, blocks select a random element with uniform probability, but the selection strategy can be customized if needed using a selector .
11.title: Item selection

110.body: A hint is a compile-time operation that informs the Rant compiler that the next program element is expected to print to the output.
110.title: Hint

111.body: Resolution refers to the process of producing an output from a block, after which the block is referred to as 'resolved.'
111.title: Resolution

112.body: The component of the Rant runtime that handles block resolution.
112.title: Resolver

113.body: A sink is an operation that suppresses the output of a program element while still allowing its execution.
113.title: Sink

12.body:
A group of blocks can be "entangled" so that they all coordinate their selections. # Create a selector named 'a'
<$sync = [mksel:one]>
# Both blocks use the `sync` selector, so they're entangled
[sel:<sync>]{Dogs|Cats} say \"[sel:<sync>]{woof|meow}!\" ##
Possible outputs:
- Dogs say "woof!"
- Cats say "meow!"
##
12.title: Entanglement

13.body: Blocks also act as scopes for local variables. Any variables created inside of a block are destroyed immediately after the block resolves.
13.title: Variable scope

14.body: Blocks used as function bodies and dynamic accessor keys are "linear" blocks: they can only contain one element and do not consume block attributes. Attempting to use a multi-element block in these contexts will cause a compiler error. This design consideration prevents function calls and accessors from unintentionally consumiung block attributes unless the user explicitly adds an inner block.
14.title: Restrictions

15.body: Functions contain code that can be executed arbitrarily. The Rant standard library includes several native functions, but you can also define your own.
15.title: Functions

16.body:
Function calls use the following syntax: # Function with no arguments
[func-name] # Function with one argument
[func-name: arg1] # Function with multiple arguments, delimited by ';'
[func-name: arg1; arg2]
16.title: Calling functions

17.title: Defining functions

18.title: Optional parameters

19.body:
Functions support variadic parameters with the special symbols * and +. A * parameter is optional and defaults to an empty list, while a + parameter is required and must contain at least one element. Functions may only have up to one variadic parameter, and it must appear last in the signature. [$how-many:items*] { [len:<items>]
} [how-many: foo; bar; baz] # Outputs "3"
19.title: Variadic parameters

2.body: In Rant, text is considered as a combination of two types of tokens: fragments and whitespace . Any string of text is a valid Rant program.
2.title: Text

20.body:
It is sometimes necessary to pass a function as a value rather than define it with a name, so that it can be called elsewhere later on. This can be done using closures , which are an implementation of anonymous functions with the ability to "capture" external variables. TODO: Provide variable capture examples Basic closure syntax with no parameters consists of a ? symbol inside brackets preceding the function body. # Creates a closure and places it on the output
[?]{A|B|C|D}
20.title: Closures

21.body: If you want to add parameters to a closure, specify the parameter names as you would with a normal function inside the closure's signature: [?:param1;param2]{ ... }
21.title: Parameterized closures

22.title: Calling anonymous functions

23.body: Comments are used to annotate code without affecting its behavior. This is useful for adding descriptions to your code that offer further explanation of the functionality. There are two types of comments in Rant: single-line and multi-line.
23.title: Comments

24.body:
A single-line comment begins with the # character and terminates at the end of the current line. They do not have to start at the beginning of a line. # This is a comment
{A|B|C} # This is an inline comment
24.title: Single-line comments

25.body:
A multi-line comment can span multiple lines and is enclosed by two # characters on each end: ##
This is
a multi-line
comment
##
25.title: Multi-line comments

26.body: It will, of course, be necessary to sometimes print reserved characters, or characters that cannot be typed on a standard keyboard. To this end, Rant offers escape sequences.
26.title: Escape sequences

27.body: Any reserved (and most non-reserved) characters can be printed by prefixing each one with a backslash character: \{This text will print with braces around it\}
27.title: Character escape sequences

28.body: Certain characters are not interpreted verbatim when escaped, and instead have special meaning. Here's a list of them: Escape sequence Output character \r Carriage return (U+000D) \n Line feed (U+000A) \s Space (U+0020) \t Tab (U+0009) \0 Null character (U+0000) \xXX UTF-8 character code [See below]
28.title: Special escape sequences

29.body: Escape sequences can also be used to print characters by their Unicode code point in hexadecimal format: \xE4 # 'ä'
29.title: Unicode escape sequences

3.body:
A fragment is defined in Rant as any sequence of characters that: contains no whitespace, contains no reserved characters (e.g. braces, brackets, etc.) Rant will output any fragment verbatim. # Prints "Hello"
Hello
3.title: Fragments

30.body: Rant programs can define and use variables of several types. Because Rant is a dynamically-typed langauge, variables have no type constraints; the type of a variable is determined by the type of its current value.
30.title: Variables

31.body: Rant currently supports nine value types: Type name Description Pass type string Sequence of UTF-8 characters by-value integer 64-bit signed integer by-value float 64-bit double-precision float by-value bool Boolean value by-value function Function/closure by-ref list List of values by-ref map String-keyed collection of values by-ref special Handle to internal runtime data, such as a selector by-ref empty Unit type representing "null" value by-value
31.title: Value types

32.body: All variable access operations are enclosed in angle brackets. Variable accessors have three subtypes: definitions , assignments , and getters .
32.title: Basic syntax

33.body:
Defining a variable creates it in the current scope, but may not necessarily initialize it with a value. All variable definitions begin with the $ symbol. # Define a variable `name` but leave it empty (value is `<>`)
<$name> # Define a variable `name` and assign it the string "Nick"
<$name = Nick>
33.title: Definition

34.body:
Variable assignments include a variable name and value separated by a = symbol. # Overwrite value on existing variable `name`
<name = Nicholas>
34.title: Assignment

35.body:
A variable getter only requires the name and adds the variable's value to the output. Attempting to retrieve a variable that does not exist results in a runtime error. # Get value of `name` (note the lack of '$')
My name is <name>. # Prints "My name is Nicholas."
35.title: Getters

36.body:
To represent the lack of a value, Rant has the empty type, which has only one possible value, represented by the token <>. <$nothing = <>> # i.e. <$nothing>
[type:<nothing>] # empty
36.title: The empty type

37.body: The two boolean values are represented by the keywords true and false. These keywords can still be used as fragments when not used alone, as their string representations are simply "true" and "false"; however, if they are passed on their own and need to be strings, you will need to put them in a string literal.
37.title: Boolean values

38.body:
In order to resolve type ambiguities, Rant follows a few rules to infer types for certain kinds of values: A number without a decimal place becomes an integer <$val = 123>
[type:<val>] # integer A number with a decimal place becomes a float <$val = 123.0>
[type:<val>] # float Any value containing fragments or whitespace is always coerced to a string <val = 99 bottles of beer>
# Since there are fragments and whitespace, it's a string
[type:<val>] # string <val = 99 99>
# Since there is whitespace between the numbers, the value is still a string
[type:<val>] # string Multiple values of any type are always coerced to a single string, as long as one of the values isn't <> <$val = 10 20 30 40 50>
# Even though they are all integer tokens, they are treated as text
[type:<val>] # string Multiple empties are coerced to a single <> [type:<><>] # empty
38.title: Implicit type coercion

39.body:
Variables in a parent scope can be non-destructively overridden in child scopes by defining a variable of the same name. # Define variable `a` in parent scope
<$a = foo>
a = <a>\n
{ # Define another variable `a` in child scope # Parent variable is not affected <$a = bar> a = <a>\n
}
# Parent variable takes over after child scope exits
a = <a> ## Output: a = foo a = bar a = foo
##
39.breadcrumbs: Language features » Overriding variables from a parent scope
39.title: Overriding variables from a parent scope

4.body: All sequences of whitespace in a Rant program are normalized to a single space by default. Rant is very selective about the whitespace it prints. By default, whitespace included in a Rant program is only printed if it is between any two of the following: Fragments Numbers Getters Blocks containing any of the above Blocks that satisfy the aforementioned requirement All other whitespace (including line breaks) is ignored. Escaped whitespace (\t, \s, etc.) are exempt from this rule. TODO: Add examples
4.title: Whitespace

40.body: Rant's variable system has two collection types: lists and maps .
40.title: Collections

41.body:
Lists are resizable arrays of values. They may contain multiple types of values. Lists are initialized using a pair of parentheses containing the list elements, separated by semicolons: # A pair of parentheses is treated like an empty list
<$empty-list = ()> # Initialize a list with one empty element
<$one-empty = (<>)> # Create a list with two empty elements
<$two-empty = (;)> # Short for (<>;<>) # Create a list of numbers
<$lucky-numbers = (1; 2; 3; 5; 7; 11; 13)> # Create a list of lists
<$important-lists = ((A; B; C); (D; E; F))>
41.title: Lists

42.body:
Maps are un-ordered collections of key-value pairs, where each key is unique. Map keys are always strings: even if you try to use a non-string as a map key, it will be automatically converted to a string first. Maps use similar syntax to lists, but with some extra requirements: The @ symbol must appear before the opening ( to identify the collection as a map. Each element must be a key-value pair, with the key and value separated by an = symbol. Map keys come in two flavors: Static keys: Evaluated at compile-time. They must be identifiers or string literals. Dynamic keys: Evaluated at run-time. They must be blocks. # Create an empty map
<$empty-map = @()> # Create a map with various value types
<$secret-key = occupation>
<$person = @( name = John; age = 25; "favorite color" = {red|green|blue}; {<secret-key>} = programmer
)>
42.title: Maps

43.body:
Variable accessors can also access individual elements in lists and maps by using the access operator /. <$person = @( name = Bob; age = 30; hobbies = (programming;hiking)
)> name = <person/name>\n
age = <person/age>\n
hobbies = [join:<person/hobbies>;,\s] ## Output: name = Bob age = 30 hobbies = programming, hiking
## Additionally, a variable access path does not need to be made out of entirely constants. You can use a block to resolve to a key or index. Map example <$my-map = @( a = foo; b = bar; c = baz
)> <my-map/{a|b|c}>
# Outputs "foo", "bar", or "baz" List example <$my-list = (foo;bar;baz)> <my-list/0> # "foo"
<my-list/1> # "bar"
<my-list/2> # "baz"
<my-list/{[n:0;2]}> # "foo", "bar", or "baz"
43.breadcrumbs: Language features » Retrieving values from collections
43.title: Retrieving values from collections

44.body: Constructs are special runtime variables that Rant can natively interact with to tailor the output of a program. There are several construct types currently supported in Rant, divided into the following categories: Block attributes Formatters Targets
44.title: Constructs

45.body: Block attributes are a set of constructs that control various aspects of block behavior. There are several block attributes available that the user can set via the standard library.
45.title: Block attributes

46.body: By setting the repetitions attribute, you can control how many times the next encountered block will run. This attribute is set with the [rep] function.
46.title: Repetitions

48.body: The separator attribute controls what is printed between each block repetition. It is set using the [sep] function.
48.title: Separator

49.body:
[rep:4][sep:" and "]
It just keeps {going}... # Output:
# It just keeps going and going and going and going...
49.title: Example

5.body:
Because Rant's whitespace rules are quite strict, it is sometimes necessary to give the compiler additional information about the structure of your output. This can be achieved by adding hints (symbolized by a ') to your code. A hint informs the compiler that the next element of code will print to the output, and that the whitespace between it and another printing element should be included. The following elements are implicitly hinted: Numbers Variable getters Blocks containing at least one fragment, number, getter, hinted element, or nested block that meets this requirement The act of a block inheriting a hint from its contents is known as "taking the hint." # Implicitly hinted (block contains fragments)
The coin landed on {Heads|Tails}. # Explicitly hint the function call so the compiler knows it prints something
Your lucky number is '[n:1;100].
5.title: Hinting

50.body: The selector attribute controls how Rant chooses which branch of a block to take. It does this using a special state machine object, which must be created separately but can be shared between blocks to coordinate their behavior.
50.title: Selector

51.body:
# Print every element of the block in a random order with no duplicates <$s=[mksel:deck]> # Create a "deck" selector
[sel:<s>] # Apply the selector
[rep:all] # Set repetitions
[sep:,\s] # Set separator
{A|B|C|D|E|F|G|H} # Output
# F, C, E, G, B, H, D, A
51.title: Example

52.body: The Rant runtime maintains a stack of "attribute frames", which store block attributes. The resolver always reads attributes from the topmost frame in the attribute frame stack. This stack can be used to limit the scope of block attributes. The attribute frame stack can be accessed with the [af-*] class of functions.
52.title: Attribute frames

53.body: Formatters are constructs that can apply various formatting filters to program output.
53.title: Formatters

55.body: The number formatter controls how Rant converts numeric values (integers and floats) to strings in the program output.
55.title: Number formatter

56.body: The whitespace formatter controls how whitespace is written to the program output.
56.title: Whitespace formatter

57.body: The Rant Standard Library contains many useful and some essential functions that are natively implemented in the Rant runtime itself.
57.title: Standard library

59.body: Prints the first argument that isn't the empty value <>.
59.title: [alt: a; b+]

6.body:
If you want to suppress the output of a code element, you can sink it with the _ operator. Sinking an element has the opposite effect of hinting: it will be marked as "non-printing" and any whitespace between it and another non-printing element will also be ignored. Only fragments and numbers cannot be sinked; the _ character will be interpreted as text in such contexts. Blocks that are sinked cannot take a hint. {Now you see me...} # Prints like normal
_{Now you don't.} # Prints nothing
Goodbye _{cruel} world! # Prints "Goodbye world!"
_Fragment # Prints "_Fragment", as fragments cannot be sinked
6.title: Sinking

60.body: Calls the function func with the argument list args. Errors Causes a runtime error if either of the following are true: func isn't a function args isn't a list
60.title: [call: func; args]

61.body: Returns the seed value that the program was run with.
61.title: [seed]

62.body: Returns the name of value's type. The type name can be any of the following: string float integer bool function list map special empty
62.title: [type: value]

63.body: Immediately exits the current scope and returns value to the caller instead of the current output. If [return] is called without an argument, the output from the function will be returned instead.
63.title: [return: value]

65.body: Prints a uniformly random decimal digit. If count is specified, repeats count times.
65.title: [dec: count?]

66.body: Prints a uniformly random lowercase hexadecimal digit. If count is specified, repeats count times.
66.title: [hex: count?]

67.body:
Prints a random integer with uniform distribution between min and max (both inclusive). Example You roll the dice and get '[n:1;6] and '[n:1;6].
# You roll the dice and get 2 and 5.
67.title: [n: min; max]

68.body: Prints a random float with uniform distribution between min (inclusive) and max (exclusive).
68.title: [nf: min; max]

7.body:
If you want to treat any text as a single fragment, you can wrap it in a string literal using double quotes: " This text is indented" They even work over several lines: "This
text
has
several
lines"
7.title: String literals

70.body: Splits the input text by sep into a list of strings. If sep is omitted, splits into characters.
70.title: [split: text; sep?]

71.body: Segments the input text into a list of strings of size length.
71.title: [seg: text; size]

77.body: Gets the modulus of two values.
77.title: [mod: lhs; rhs]

78.body: Multiplies two values, then adds another value to the result.
78.title: [mul-add: lhs; rhs; add]

8.body: A block is a unit of Rant code subdivided into zero or more parts.
8.title: Blocks

80.body: Gets the reciprocal of a value.
80.title: [recip: n]

82.body: Prints the elements of a list in order separated by the separator value.
82.title: [join: separator; list]

83.body: Adds a value to the end of a list.
83.title: [push: list; value]

84.body: Removes the last value from a list and prints it.
84.title: [pop: list]

85.body: Inserts value into a list or map at the position pos. If collection is a list, pos must be an integer. If collection is a map, pos may be any non-empty value. Errors Causes a runtime error if any of the following are true: collection is not a list or map pos is an unsupported type for the provided collection collection is a list and pos is out of range
85.title: [insert: collection; value; pos]

86.body: Removes the value at the pos from a list or map. If collection is a list, pos must be an integer. If collection is a map, pos may be any non-empty value. Errors Causes a runtime error if any of the following are true: collection is not a list or map pos is an unsupported type for the provided collection collection is a list and pos is out of range
86.title: [remove: collection; pos]

87.body: Removes the value at pos from a list or map and prints it. If collection is a list, pos must be an integer. If collection is a map, pos may be any non-empty value. Errors Causes a runtime error if any of the following are true: collection is not a list or map pos is an unsupported type for the provided collection collection is a list and pos is out of range Errors Causes a runtime error if collection is a list and the pos is out of range.
87.title: [take: collection; pos]

88.body: Removes all elements from a list or map. Errors Causes a runtime error if collection is not a list or map.
88.title: [clear: collection]

89.body: Prints the length of obj as an integer. For strings, this is the number of bytes; for lists and maps, this is the number of elements. All other value types give a length of 0.
89.title: [len: obj]

9.body:
A block is defined by a set of braces containing zero or more sections of Rant code separated by vertical pipes (|). Here are a few examples: {} # Empty block
{A} # Block with one element
{A|B} # Block with multiple elements
9.title: Syntax

91.body: Pushes a new attribute frame onto the attribute frame stack, overriding the previous one.
91.title: [af-push]

92.body: Removes the topmost attribute frame from the attribute frame stack, handing control back to the previous one. Errors Popping the last attribute frame results in a runtime error.
92.title: [af-pop]

93.body: Prints the current size of the attribute frame stack.
93.title: [af-count]

94.body: Creates and returns a selector of the specified type.
94.title: [mksel: selector-type]

95.body: Type name Description one Selects the same, random element each time. forward Selects each element in a wrapping sequence from left to right. reverse Selects each element in a wrapping reverse sequence from right to left. deck Selects each element once in a random sequence, then reshuffles. deck-loop Selects each element once in a wrapping random sequence, without reshuffling. deck-clamp Selects each element once in a random sequence, repeating the final element. forward-clamp Selects each element from left to right, then repeats the right-most element. reverse-clamp Selects each element from right to left, then repeats the left-most element. no-double Ensures that no one element index is selected twice in a row.
95.title: Selector types

96.body:
Sets the repetition count for the next block to reps. The value of reps must be non-negative. Example # Print the fragment 3 times
[r:3]{ha}
# hahaha # Print the fragment between 3 and 8 times
[r:[n:3;8]]{ha}
# hahahaha
# hahahahahahaha
# hahaha
# hahahahaha
# ...
96.title: [rep: reps]

97.body: Sets the selector for the next block.
97.title: [sel: selector]

98.body: Sets the separator value for the next block to separator. The value of separator may be a string, number, or function. If it is a function, it will be called separately for each usage and its return value will be printed.
98.title: [sep: separator]
